java.util.List<Expression> getArguments()
Returns a list of the method call's arguments.

Calling this method equals an getArguments(null) call.

Returns:
A list of the method call's arguments. If there are no arguments null will be returned.

getArguments

java.util.List<Expression> getArguments(java.util.List<Expression> pList)
Returns a list of the method call's arguments.

Parameters:
pList - If this argument isn't null the arguments will be added to this list and this list object will be returned. Otherwise a new list will be created for the result.
Returns:

getGenericTypeArguments

java.util.List<GenericTypeArgument> getGenericTypeArguments()
Returns a list of generic type arguments that may have been stated with the method invocation.

Example: for a method call like '<T> anyMethodCall(anyArgs)' this method would return a list that contains just one generic type parameter that represents the type T stated by <T>.

Returns:
A list of generic type arguments. If there are no generic type arguments null will be returned.
See Also:
getGenericTypeArguments(List)

getMethodInvocation

PrimaryExpression getMethodInvocation()
Returns the method invocation.

Such an invocation is a more or less complicated primary expression ending with the methods identifier. A formal example could look like: 

     anyPrimaryExpression.anyMethodCall(...).anotherMethodCall(...)
. Calling this method for the example above the primary expression representing 'anyPrimaryExpression.anyMethodCall(...).anotherMethodCall' will be returned. This primary expression would be of type DotExpression with another DotExpression as the left expression and an Identifier object (i.e. the method's identifier) as the right expression.

The most trivial primary expression would be the method's identifier, of course.

Returns:
The method invocation.
See Also:
getIdentifier()
